      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(ios): improve onboarding gateway connection flow",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\niOS onboarding made gateway connection feel brittle: users had to choose between QR/setup code, LAN discovery, and remote/Tailscale concepts without a clear first-run path. Tailscale also needed to feel like a real path for users who already have a gateway on their tailnet, while keeping the existing QR/deep-link auth contract tight.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThis replaces the first onboarding screen with a connection-path chooser for QR/setup code, local auto-find, Tailscale/remote, and manual setup. It adds a first-class Tailscale entry path for MagicDNS/Tailscale Serve URLs and blocks raw `100.x` IP setup on iOS so first-run remote onboarding stays on secure transports.\n\nIt also improves auth recovery copy by distinguishing token-missing, password-missing, and generic unauthorized gateway states. Generic QR/setup-code/deep-link parsing still rejects plaintext CGNAT setup codes, and this PR no longer persists a plaintext Tailscale route exception for reconnect.\n\n## User Impact\n\nNew users get a clearer onboarding decision tree and a smoother path for already-on-tailnet devices: paste a MagicDNS name or Tailscale Serve URL, then connect. If a user enters a raw `100.x` tailnet IP, the app now stops before probe/connect and tells them to use the gateway's MagicDNS or Tailscale Serve URL instead.\n\nThe QR/setup-code auth contract remains unchanged: raw gateway token/password are not added to QR output by this PR.\n\n## Evidence\n\n![iOS onboarding secure Tailscale proof](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/Solvely-Colin/e990af94db65d2f14736ed11caba0e0f/raw/4b232dabc8f888d98ce7212ce7402fe3b6f923b9/ios-onboarding-secure-tailscale-proof.gif)\n\nGitHub-hosted redacted proof packet: https://gist.github.com/Solvely-Colin/e990af94db65d2f14736ed11caba0e0f\n\nVisual proof:\n- [Connection path chooser with secure Tailscale copy](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/Solvely-Colin/e990af94db65d2f14736ed11caba0e0f/raw/be517e2bfe1df53412c40e5fef004ca22409fc02/01-connection-paths-secure-tailscale-redacted.jpg)\n- [Raw IP blocked before probe/connect, redacted](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/Solvely-Colin/e990af94db65d2f14736ed11caba0e0f/raw/98d4a91b9153982841aa59dc07e340ba7836880f/02-raw-ip-blocked-redacted.jpg)\n- [Sanitized proof summary](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/Solvely-Colin/e990af94db65d2f14736ed11caba0e0f/raw/51c7408c1f3d19605f15eada9b7e187ae2ec59dd/github-proof-summary.md)\n\nCode/test proof:\n- `xcodebuild -quiet test -project apps/ios/OpenClaw.xcodeproj -scheme OpenClawLogicTests -configuration Debug -destination 'platform=iOS Simulator,name=iPhone 17' -derivedDataPath apps/ios/build/CodexOnboardingP2LogicTests` -> passed\n- `swift test --package-path apps/shared/OpenClawKit --filter DeepLinksSecurityTests` -> passed, 17 tests\n- `git diff --check` -> passed\n- `.agents/skills/autoreview/scripts/autoreview --mode local` -> clean, no accepted/actionable findings\n- XcodeBuildMCP `build_run_sim` on iPhone 17 simulator -> succeeded after secure-only patch\n\nKnown existing build warnings remain in unrelated files: `NodeAppModel.swift`, `TalkModeManager.swift`, and `OpenClawChatUI/ChatViewModel.swift`.\n",
